s, see complex connections, spatial vision suggest technical competence but not explicit. Leadership good.\n\nCandidate B: keeps calm in crisis, 100% reliable, good at assessing weather, excellent computer skills, can be grumpy, can be uncooperative, makes nasty remarks about colleagues. Positive teamwork: calm, reliability, weather assessment, computer skills. Negative: grumpy, uncooperative, nasty remarks.\n\nCandidate C: can make correct decisions quickly, difficulty communicating ideas, regarded as egocentric, not very willing to further his education, handles stress very well, creates positive atmosphere with crew. So strengths: quick decision, stress handling, positive atmosphere. Weaknesses: communication difficulty, egocentric, not willing to further education.\n\nCandidate D: responds to unexpected events adequately, can concentrate very well, solves problems extremely well, takes responsibility seriously, regarded as arrogant, relatively weak leadership skills, hot temper, known as know-it-all? Actually \"regarded as arrogant\" and \"relatively weak leadership skills\". Also \"takes responsibility seriously\". No explicit reliability, technical competence not explicit, but problem solving and concentration suggest competence. Calmness under pressure ambiguous due to hot temper.\n\nNow we need to evaluate holistically for long-distance pilot: reliability, technical competence, calm under pressure, decision making, teamwork, professional development.\n\nWe have gaps: reliability for A and D unknown. Technical competence for A and D unknown (but we have some hints). Leadership for D weak. Teamwork for C maybe limited due to communication difficulty. C's egocentric may affect crew cooperation. B has teamwork positives but also uncooperative and nasty remarks.\n\nWe need to ask other agents for missing info: maybe ask about Candidate A's reliability, Candidate D's technical competence, Candidate D's leadership strengths, Candidate C's technical competence, Candidate C's reliability, Candidate D's calmness, etc.\n\nBut we already asked about A reliability and D technical competence and got no explicit info. Could ask about Candidate C's reliability and technical competence. Also ask about Candidate D's reliability. Also ask about Candidate A's calmness under pressure. Also ask about Candidate B's teamwork negatives? But we have that.\n\nWe need to produce a public message that includes reasoning, maybe ask targeted questions to fill gaps. Then give a vote based on current info, but we can hold off? The instruction: \"When you find yourself leaning toward a candidate, actively look for reasons you might be wrong. Ask other agents targeted questions.\" So we can give a tentative vote but also ask questions.\n\nWe need to output vote in metadata. Should we vote now? Probably we can give a tentative vote but can be changed later. The system expects a vote. We'll give a vote based on current info: Candidate A has strong leadership, situational awareness, but lacks reliability info. Candidate B is reliable and calm but has teamwork issues. Candidate C good decision, stress handling, positive atmosphere, but communication issues and egocentric. Candidate D strong problem solving, responsibility, but arrogance, weak leadership, hot temper.\n\nLong-distance flights require reliability, calm, teamwork, technical competence. B seems reliable and calm, but uncooperative and nasty remarks could be problematic for crew. C's communication difficulty could be a problem. A's leadership and situational awareness are good, but unknown reliability. D's arrogance and hot temper are concerning.\n\nThus B seems strongest on reliability and calm, but teamwork negatives may be mitigated? However uncooperative and nasty remarks are serious for crew. C's positive atmosphere may offset communication difficulty? But egocentric and unwilling to further education is concerning for long-term development.\n\nProbably B is best if teamwork issues can be managed, but we need more info on B's cooperation. We have negative notes: grumpy, uncooperative, nasty remarks. That seems significant.\n\nMaybe A could be best if reliability is assumed? But we have no reliability info. Could ask other agents about A's reliability.\n\nThus we should ask: \"Do you have any information on Candidate A's reliability or any evidence of their responsibility?\" Also ask about Candidate D's reliability. Also ask about Candidate C's technical competence. Also ask about Candidate C's reliability.\n\nLet's ask those.\n\nNow produce PUBLIC_MESSAGE: summarize known attributes, note gaps, ask targeted questions, and give tentative vote maybe \"Candidate B\" but note uncertainties.\n\nWe'll include vote in metadata."}
